It's been cool to see the rationalist community change so much over the past few years.

Collective trauma in the rationalist community and the hyper independence that it seems to provide.

I'm really not involved in the community at all, so all of this is an outsiders perspective.

I wonder if the rationalist community just felt like they alone needed to carry the weight of the world. It's both misunderstanding how much an individual is repsonsible for.



I have a bunch of really mixed up feelings about the rationalist community, circa 2017-2018. I wouldn't call myself a member of the community, but as a SF resident working in tech / ML / the startup scene, I frequently interacted with core rationalists. 

## Perfectionism
I, too, felt responsible for the parts of the world that I had control over. I thought, in my perfectionist way, that I had to do the best job ever in dealing with it. The community seemed to feel responsible for figuring out the best solution for the world's problems. Doing a net-positive thing, somehow didn't feel good enough. It had to solve the global optimization problem.

My perfectionist tendencies loved global optimization problems. I factored everyone in my life into my grand schemes, giving my friends complicated schedules planned down to the fifteen minute mark of where we would be and who we would be meeting up with. I also planned no slack. If we got off schedule, we were behind.

Most times, it worked out. I could cram an impossible number of hangouts, games, and chores in a day. When it didn't work out, I melted into a puddle of anxiety and stress. If someone else was late, or god forbid the train was late, I frantically rescheduled everything else that day. 

I've been told my capacity for dealing with logistics is a great strength. I'm here to say that I've completely burned it out. Today, the thought of planning for anything is anxiety inducing. If I have to transport my body between cities, I can get literally nothing else done that day. 

So I don't think always trying to solve the global optimization problem is a good thing. Even if you think you know what the solution is, it doesn't fall to your shoulders to implement it. People have different strengths, and we can contribute to different capacities. Do something you enjoy doing that makes the neighborhood around you a little better. Everyone experiences and sees different things, you can be open to helping in ways that you enjoy and are good at, but just because you could do something, doesn't mean you have to. 

### A failure mode: 
I have a friend who decided several years ago that he loved another individual's research and wanted to help advance it as much as possible. This friend signed up for a job working with the researcher and doing all the grunge infrastructure work. He hated it. Surely some people love setting up machines to run complicated models in parallel, but he was not one of them. He still felt that he wanted to contribute, and furthering this research felt like the most important thing he could be doing. He couldn't shake the feeling that he was incompetent (I'm sure he wasn't. He just hated this job and didn't want to do it.) and that he was thus useless. 

This is a fixed mindset. I wished my friend could just close their eyes for a moment and think about the things that made them happy. Then choose something within the scope of things that bring them joy and contribute in a small way to a cause they find meaningful. 

To be honest, I wish I could do that too. But, easier said than done, it's hard to say what brings me joy! And I find so many causes meaningful!

## Collective action

That being said, I've always respected how effectively the rationalist community could rally behind a cause. Since people bought the idea that they should do the most effective thing, all it took was determining a "thing."

I'm simplifying, of course, but the number of people who make big life changes to advance the cause is impressive to me. 

This might also be true with other movements as well, and perhaps with political campaigns. I just happen to have the front row seats to this one. 

The frequent discussions about long-term AI risk in the rationalist community ran absolutely counter to my work place where up until very recently, short-term AI risk (like perpetuating harmful stereotypes in decision making systems and violating privacy expectations of data used for training) were not even widely discussed. 


